s/002447.html |archive-date=17 May 2008 }}</ref> He signed for Grays for a third time on 19 August 2008, on loan until the end of the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309]] season.<ref name=\"Thurgood Back Again\">{{cite news|title=Thurgood Back Again |url=http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/news/archives/002674.html |publisher=greysathletic.co.uk |date=19 August 2008 |access-date=19 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809152242/http://graysathletic.co.uk/news/archives/002674.html |archive-date=9 August 2011 }}</ref> This was cut short though when he was released by Gillingham on 23 January 2009, at which point he joined Grays permanently again until the end of the season.<ref name=\"Thurgood leaves Gills\">{{cite news\n| title = Thurgood leaves Gills\n| url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11750_4838912,00.html\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 23 January 2009\n| accessdate = 23 January 2009}}</ref> After the end of the season, in May, he joined [[Football League Two|League Two]] team [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] on a two-year contract.<ref name=\"Daggers sign Thurgood from Grays\">{{cite news\n| title = Daggers sign Thurgood from Grays\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/dagenham_and_redbridge/8064156.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 22 May 2009\n| accessdate = 22 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring November 2009 he sustained an injury which eventually forced him to retire, aged just 28.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thurgood forced to retire at 28 |url=http://www.daggers.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10692~2159793,00.html |work=daggers.co.uk |publisher=[[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] |date=20 September 2010 |accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nHowever, after a successful period with playing for Grays Athletic's reserve team, Thurgood signed for the [[Isthmian League]] Division One club on 11 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/news/new-signings-402249.html | title = New signings | publisher = Grays Athletic F.C. | date = 11 October 2011 | accessdate = 11 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Thurgood signed for [[Conference South]] club [[Thurrock F.C.|Thurrock]],<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.footballconference.co.uk/news/details.php?news_id=5818 |title=Thurrock sign Thurgood |publisher=Football Conference |date=5 November 2011}}</ref> and returned for another spell in March 2017.\n\n==Honours==\n*[[FA Trophy]]: 2005, 2006\n*[[Conference South]] (VI): 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10416~9022,00.html Stuart Thurgood player profile] at gillinghamfootballclub.com\n*{{Soccerbase|24031}}\n*{{Soccerbase|36908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thurgood, Stuart}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Enfield Town]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n[[Category:England semi-pro international footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Japan]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Shimizu S-Pulse players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grays Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dagenham & Redbridge F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:East Thurrock United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:VCD Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Isthmian League players]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_Thurgood"}
{"title_page": "Stuart Taylor (footballer, born 1980)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Stuart Taylor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Stuart Taylor\n| image                = Stuart Taylor.JPG\n| image_size           = 200\n| caption              = Taylor warming up for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2008\n| fullname             = Stuart James Taylor<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1980|11|28|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/stuart-taylor-28/ |title=Stuart Taylor |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place          = [[Romford]], England\n| height               = {{convert|1.98|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://southamptonfc.com/first-team/stuart-taylor |title=First team: Stuart Taylor |publisher=Southampton F.C. |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n| position             = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub          = \n| clubnumber           = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| years1  = 1997\u20132005 | clubs1  = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]                                  | caps1  = 18 | goals1  = 0\n| years2  = 1999      | clubs2  = \u2192 [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] (loan)           | caps2  = 4  | goals2  = 0\n| years3  = 2000      | clubs3  = \u2192 [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] (loan)           | caps3  = 10 | goals3  = 0\n| years4  = 2001      | clubs4  = \u2192 [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] (loan) | caps4  = 6  | goals4  = 0\n| years5  = 2004\u20132005 | clubs5  = \u2192 [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] (loan)           | caps5  = 10 | goals5  = 0\n| years6  = 2005\u20132009 | clubs6  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]                          | caps6  = 12 | goals6  = 0\n| years7  = 2009      | clubs7  = \u2192 [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] (loan)               | caps7  = 8  | goals7  = 0\n| years8  = 2009\u20132012 | clubs8  = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]                  | caps8  = 0  | goals8  = 0\n| years9  = 2012\u20132014 | clubs9  = [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]                                  | caps9  = 4  | goals9  = 0\n| years10 = 2013      | clubs10 = \u2192 [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] (loan)                 | caps10 = 0  | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2014\u20132015 | clubs11 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]                        | caps11 = 3  | goals11 = 0\n| years12 = 2016\u20132018| clubs12 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]                          | caps12 = 0  | goals12 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1997      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20131999 | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 5 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1999      | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 2 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2001      | nationalteam4 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 3 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update             = 13:05, 2 May 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Stuart James Taylor''' (born 28 November 1980) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] and is currently a free agent following his release from [[Premier League]] club [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2018-06-28/stuart-taylor-southampton-football-club-end-of-contract|work=Southampton FC|title=Taylor to depart Saints|date=28 June 2018|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Taylor began his career with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], winning the [[2001\u201302 FA Premier League|2001\u201302 Premier League]] and [[2002\u201303 FA Cup]] and representing England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] level. He was spoken of as a future replacement for Arsenal and England goalkeeper [[David Seaman]] but after other goalkeepers were signed, he struggled to get playing time after 2003 and he joined [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2005.<ref name=leftout>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/13/sports/soccer/premier-league-goalkeeper-stuart-taylor.html|title=This Premier League Player's Position? Left Out|website=The New York Times|author=Rory Smith|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nInitially second-choice behind [[Thomas S\u00f8rensen]], Taylor was again supplanted by other keepers and pushed down the pecking order. He left Aston Villa in 2009, having played only 12 league matches in 4 seasons. He has since been contracted with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]], [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. Taylor has spent most of his career as a third-choice goalkeeper; he has made only 95 career appearances, played in just 10 games since a loan spell at [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] ended in May 2009 and hasn't played at all since 2015.<ref name=leftout/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Arsenal===\nTaylor was born in [[Romford]], London.<ref>{{Hugman|19357|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref> After a brief spell as a teenager with [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]],<ref name=leftout/> Taylor joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 1997 as a youth player. He made his Arsenal debut in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] game against [[Ipswich Town]] in November 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/worthington_cup/1000608.stm|title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Ipswich |publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 November 2000 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> While at Arsenal he was loaned out to [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]], [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]]  and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/teams/madejski-men/goalkeeper/stuart-taylor/|title=Stuart Taylor: Profile|website=Reading FC.co.uk|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319084925/https://www.readingfc.co.uk/teams/madejski-men/goalkeeper/stuart-taylor/|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Leicester snap up keeper on loan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/4023111.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 November 2004|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref> His league debut for Arsenal came in a 3\u20131 win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in November 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1671459.stm |title=Barthez errors gift Arsenal win |publisher= BBC Sport|date=25 November 2001 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/1670055.stm |title=Taylor's time at last |publisher= BBC Sport|date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> He went on to make ten League appearances in Arsenal's [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302]] [[Premier League]]-winning season, thus qualifying him for a winners' medal. This feat was achieved in the final match against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], with the title already won. [[Richard Wright (footballer)|Richard Wright]] started the game with Taylor upon nine appearances. Manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] substituted Wright in the 85th minute of play for Taylor who thus earned a medal with this cap.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/1978471.stm|title=Henry sparks Arsenal party|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin |last=Mitchell |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/may/12/match.sport1|title=Henry enters party spirit|work=The Guardian |date=12 May 2002|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Arsenal he was tipped to become [[David Seaman]]'s successor.<ref name=leftout/> However, although he saw off competition from [[Alex Manninger]] and Wright, the signings of [[Jens Lehmann]] and [[Manuel Almunia]] in 2003 and 2004 respectively saw him struggle for playing time. Taylor also missed the whole of the 2003\u201304 season due to a persistent shoulder problem.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Taylor out for season| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/3578339.stm|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 29 March 2004| accessdate = 13 April 2008}}</ref> After the signing of Almunia, Taylor thus became the club's third-choice goalkeeper and Wenger told Taylor that he would understand if he chose to leave.<ref name=leftout/> During his stay at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] Taylor won a league title, an FA Cup as well as two Charity Shields. Altogether he made 30 appearances in all competitions for Arsenal.<ref name=AFC>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/historic/players/stuart-taylor|title=Stuart Taylor|publisher=Arsenal F.C. |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=FAC /><ref name=CS /><ref name=CS1 />\n\n===Aston Villa===\nIn June 2005 Taylor moved to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], signing on a four-year deal.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Arsenal keeper Taylor joins Villa| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4626853.stm|publisher=BBC Sport| date = 27 June 2005| accessdate = 13 April 2008}}</ref> He became Villa's second-choice goalkeeper, behind [[Thomas S\u00f8rensen]]. Taylor recalls being told that he would play if S\u00f8rensen was injured or in poor form, but those chances \"never materialised. I kept being told I would play this game or that game, and I never did. You get your hopes up, and it's hard to take. Football is a cruel game. People tell you what they think you want to hear.\"<ref name=leftout/> During the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season he made just two appearances for the club. He saved [[Wayne Rooney]]'s penalty in a match against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 20 October 2007 during a match in which first-choice goalkeeper [[Scott Carson]] was sent off.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7043000.stm|title=Aston Villa 1\u20134 Man Utd|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 October 2007|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> When S\u00f8rensen left, Villa signed [[Brad Friedel]] and [[Brad Guzan]] at the start of the [[2008\u201309 Aston Villa F.C. season|2008\u201309 season]]. Friedel became the first choice goalkeeper with Guzan second choice and Taylor slipping down to third. This despite generally putting in good performances, when called upon. Taylor's final appearance for Villa was the game against [[Odense Boldklub|Odense BK]] in the [[2008 UEFA Intertoto Cup]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Cardiff City (loan)===\nIn a bid to find first team football,<ref name=leftout/> Taylor began to search for a short-term loan deal at a [[The Football League|Football League]] side, entering into talks with [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/footballnation/cardiff-city-fc/2009/03/14/new-bluebirds-goalkeeper-taylor-i-almost-joined-leeds-91466-23140630/|title=New Bluebirds goalkeeper Taylor: I almost joined Leeds|website=WalesOnline|publisher=Media Wales|accessdate=14 March 2009|date=14 March 2009|first=Terry|last=Phillips}}</ref> However, on 13 March 2009, a last minute offer from [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] prompted Taylor to instead opt for the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side on a one-month loan deal, becoming the third goalkeeper to sign on loan at the club during the season, after [[Tom Heaton]] and [[Dimitrios Konstantopoulos]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/7941298.stm|title=Cardiff sign Villa keeper Taylor|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 March 2009|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> He made his debut for the side two days later in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7923155.stm|title=Bristol City 1\u20131 Cardiff|date=15 March 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nTaylor continued as first choice for Cardiff throughout his first month at the club, despite the return of Tom Heaton from injury, and his loan deal was extended to the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/7997296.stm|title=McCormack hailed as Cardiff hero|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2009|accessdate=14 April 2009}}</ref> However, following a 6\u20130 defeat to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]], Taylor was dropped from the side for the final three games of the season. At the end of the campaign, he returned to [[Villa Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/footballnation/football-news/2009/05/06/cardiff-city-get-tough-after-play-off-flop-91466-23554084|title=Cardiff City get tough after play-off flop|date=6 May 2009|website=WalesOnline|publisher=Media Wales|accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\nTaylor signed for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on a free transfer on 23 June 2009, following the expiration of his contract at Villa. He officially became a Manchester City player on 1 July 2009.<ref name=\"avfc.premiumtv.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10265~1699020,00.html |title=Taylor Set To Depart |publisher=Aston Villa F.C. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626003308/http://www.avfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10265~1699020%2C00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 June 2009 |df= }}</ref> Taylor admitted taking advice from Brad Friedel, who had previously worked with manager [[Mark Hughes]] and goalkeeping coach [[Kevin Hitchcock]] at [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. On 18 July 2009, when Manchester City played the South African team [[Orlando Pirates FC|Orlando Pirates]], Taylor conceded his first two goals for the club. Signed as cover for [[Shay Given]], Taylor was promised playing time in the FA Cup and League Cup, but this also failed to materialise.<ref name=leftout/> Taylor made his only first-team appearance for the club in an FA Cup 4th round tie against [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] on 24 January 2010, which City won 4\u20132.\n\nOn 10 July, he signed a new two-year deal with the club,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Team-news/2010/July/New-contract-for-Manchester-City-goalkeeper-Stuart-Taylor |title=Stuart Taylor nets new deal |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> despite being officially released by City nine days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stuart Taylor comes back to Manchester City, nine days after getting the Eastlands boot|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1293663/Stuart-Taylor-comes-Manchester-City-days-getting-Eastlands-boot.html|newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London |date=10 July 2010|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref> Taylor also played against [[New York Red Bulls]] on 25 July 2010 in the second half in City's U.S. Tour, and conceded one goal in a 2\u20131 defeat. After the return of [[Joe Hart]] from a loan spell, Taylor once again found himself third-choice goalkeeper.<ref name=leftout/> He fell further down the pecking order, with [[Costel Pantilimon]] starting in front of him in a League Cup tie against former club Arsenal on 29 November 2011, which City won 1\u20130. After winning the 2011\u201312 Premier League title as Manchester City's third choice goalkeeper, he was released by City for a second time on 1 June 2012, alongside other goalkeeper [[Gunnar Nielsen (footballer)|Gunnar Nielsen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/content/dam/premierleague/site-content/News/publications/other/premier-league-released-list.pdf |title=FREE TRANSFER LIST 2011/12 |publisher=Premier League |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616133811/http://www.premierleague.com/content/dam/premierleague/site-content/News/publications/other/premier-league-released-list.pdf |archive-date=16 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Reading===\n[[Reading F.C.|Reading]] announced on 13 July 2012 that Taylor was currently training with them and would play a part in their first team friendly with [[AFC Wimbledon]] on 14 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Reading Football Club |title=Taylor to play part in Wimbledon game |url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10306~2848349,00.html |access-date=13 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715233543/http://www.readingfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10306~2848349%2C00.html |archive-date=15 July 2012 |df= }}</ref> On 20 August 2012 Reading manager [[Brian McDermott (footballer)|Brian McDermott]] announced that they had signed Taylor on a 1-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Reading Football CluB|title=Taylor Signs, Mikkel loaned|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/taylor-signs-mikkel-loaned-180812-320118.aspx |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> Injuries to both [[Adam Federici]] and [[Alex McCarthy]] saw Taylor make his Reading debut on 2 March in a 3\u20131 defeat to Everton in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/report-tough-toffees-win-689555.aspx |title=Report: Tough Toffees win |publisher=Reading F.C |accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> Taylor played against his former club Arsenal on 30 March 2013 in a 4\u20131 loss at the [[Emirates Stadium]]. Taylor signed a new one-year deal with Reading, keeping him at the club till June 2014, on 2 August 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor pens new deal|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/taylor-pens-new-deal-963510.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C. |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 November 2013, Taylor joined fellow Championship side [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] on an initial one-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24988135 |title=Stuart Taylor: Yeovil Town sign Reading goalkeeper on loan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=18 November 2013 }}</ref> Taylor's loan with Yeovil was cut short without making a competitive appearance after just two days due to \"personal reasons\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25020871 |title=Stuart Taylor: Reading goalkeeper leaves Yeovil after two days |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 November 2013 |accessdate=20 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTaylor's spell at Reading, found him as a backup goalkeeper to regular goalkeepers McCarthy and Federici. He left the club at the end of the 2013\u201314 season upon the expiry of his contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jobi, Mikele & Kaspars to move on|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/mcanuff-leigertwood-gorkss-leave-060514-1539505.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.}}</ref>\n\n===Leeds United===\nTaylor signed a one-year contract with Leeds United on 3 July 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Leeds United sign Stuart Taylor |url=http://www.itv.com/news/calendar/update/2014-07-03/leeds-united-sign-stuart-taylor/ |publisher=ITV |date=3 July 2014 |accessdate=3 July 2014}}</ref> Taylor revealed that he was hoping to challenge for the number 1 spot, after revealing that Leeds were also looking to sign another goalkeeper.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Taylor looking to be involved|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/dvbr8fqfh8c81pd86dj7n0lgt/title/taylor-looking-to-be-involved|publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=3 July 2014 |accessdate=3 July 2014}}</ref> On 8 July, Leeds signed a new number 1 goalkeeper in [[Marco Silvestri]] from [[Chievo Verona]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-complete-silvestri-and-bianchi-signings-1-6718003|title=Leeds United complete Silvestri and Bianchi signings|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds}}</ref> On 1 August, Taylor was assigned the Leeds number 13 shirt for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/1wncxa2kw0zr11fmlyjr0m3t53/title/squad-numbers-released|title=Squad numbers released |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nTaylor made his Leeds United debut on 12 August 2014, starting the League Cup match against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Leeds V Accrington|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/17zjc7q85j4pm1c43n56bi1r92/title/accrington-live!|publisher=Leeds United F.C. |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> Taylor started for Leeds on 27 August in the 2\u20131 defeat against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/325040/report|title=United edged out at Bradford|publisher=Sky Sports|date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nTaylor made his league debut in the game against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on 18 April 2015 in a 2\u20131 loss, with Taylor giving away a penalty.<ref>{{cite news|title= Leeds United striker Steve Morison left bemused by latest chaos at Elland Road |date=19 April 2015|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3046059/Leeds-United-striker-Steve-Morrison-left-bemused-latest-chaos-Elland-Road.html|newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London |agency=Press Association}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 May 2015, upon the expiry of his contract, Leeds announced that they would not be renewing Taylor's contract at the club.<ref>{{Cite web| title= Austin Released by Leeds United | url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/8vnxct5efa2m1vcq9ks3km08f/title/retained-list---summer-2015 | publisher= Leeds United F.C. | date= 13 May 2015| accessdate= 12 May 2015}}</ref> Taylor, who had played only 9 games between 2012 and 2015, considered retirement: \"You go round thinking things will happen, that surely you will get games, and it becomes very demoralising. I was fed up.\"<ref name=leftout/> He turned down the chance to join clubs in [[League One]] and [[League Two]] as he felt that even if he played more matches, it would be an admission that he wasn't good enough to play in the Premier League: \"People will say I am wrong, but I wanted to play at the highest level I thought I could play at. I felt I was good enough to be in the Premier League.\"<ref name=leftout/>\n\n===Southampton===\nOn 26 August 2016, after a year without a club, Taylor joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cedric Soares: Southampton defender signs new deal until 2020|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37197184|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2016|date=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor joins Saints on one-year deal|url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/20160826-stuart-taylor-southampton-announcement-3273822.aspx|publisher=Southampton F.C. |accessdate=27 August 2016|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> Taylor joined knowing he would be third-choice behind [[Fraser Forster]] and [[Alex McCarthy]]: \"nobody promised me anything. I know my role.\"<ref name=leftout/> On 13 July 2017, Southampton announced that Taylor's contract had been extended for another year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor signs new deal|url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2017-07-13/stuart-taylor-new-southampton-contract-announcement|publisher=Southampton F.C.|accessdate=13 July 2017|date=13 July 2017}}</ref> On 30 June 2018, Taylor left Southampton after his contract expired, without having made a first-team appearance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Taylor to depart Saints |url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2018-06-28/stuart-taylor-southampton-football-club-end-of-contract |publisher=Southampton F.C. |accessdate=1 July 2018 |date=28 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the ''[[New York Times]]'' in December 2017, Taylor talked about his career and the frustrations he had at barely playing and becoming known for being a third-choice keeper: \"There is definitely a perception of me... [as a man who] loves going round clubs, earning money for doing nothing.\"<ref name=leftout/> He dismissed suggestions that he \"sits around doing nothing, turning up for training, having a jolly, messing about\" and had become wealthy after spending so long in the Premier League, saying that when his playing career ends \"I will have to work. People assume I have made serious money. I really haven't.\"<ref name=leftout/> He said that \"every coach I have had, every goalkeeper I have worked with, has said I should have played 200 or 300 Premier League games. I look back at it and think the same.\"<ref name=leftout/>\n\n==International career==\nTaylor played for the [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] team at the 1999 [[FIFA World Youth Championship]] alongside [[Ashley Cole]], [[Peter Crouch]] and [[Andrew Johnson (English footballer)|Andrew Johnson]]. He was capped three times for the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] team.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 24 May 2016}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competitio